
[1]palisade

   PALISA'DE, n. A fence or fortification consisting of a row of stakes or
   posts sharpened and set firmly in the ground. In fortification, the
   posts are set two or three inches apart, parallel to the parapet in the
   covered way, to prevent a surprise.

   Palisades serve also to fortify the avenues of open forts, gorges,
   half-moons, the bottom of ditches, &c.

   PALISA'DE, v.t. To surround, inclose or fortify with stakes or posts.
